## Review Scope

Compodoc + Storybook integration added to an Nx Angular library (`ngx-smart-components`), across 4 commits on branch `uat-replay-0.13.1` vs `main`. Files changed: `.storybook/preview.ts` (new), `.storybook/tsconfig.json` (modified), `project.json` (modified), `src/lib/ngx-smart-components/ngx-smart-components.ts` (modified), `package.json` (+@compodoc/compodoc), `.gitignore`.

## Pre-Verified Package Behavior Claims

<pre_verified source="node_modules/@storybook/angular/dist/_browser-chunks/chunk-XA6C6Y3S.js" claim_id="pv-global-read">
  <claim>Storybook Angular 10.3.5 reads `__STORYBOOK_COMPODOC_JSON__` via `@storybook/global`, which resolves to `globalThis` (or `window` in browser). Setting `globalThis.__STORYBOOK_COMPODOC_JSON__` in `preview.ts` is the correct integration path in this version.</claim>
  <evidence method="Read">
    import { global as global2 } from "@storybook/global";
    var getCompodocJson = () => global2.__STORYBOOK_COMPODOC_JSON__
    // @storybook/global resolves global2 to globalThis via:
    //   if (typeof globalThis !== "undefined") { win = globalThis; }
  </evidence>
</pre_verified>

<pre_verified source="node_modules/@compodoc/compodoc" claim_id="pv-compodoc-version">
  <claim>@compodoc/compodoc 1.2.1 is installed (resolved from `^1.2.1`). Commit messages record empirical verification: signal `input()` properties appear in `inputsClass`, signal `output()` properties appear in `outputsClass`, with JSDoc descriptions -- Compodoc 1.2.1 supports Angular signal APIs.</claim>
  <evidence method="Read">
    package-lock.json: "node_modules/@compodoc/compodoc": { "version": "1.2.1" }
    Commit 4e31d8f body: "Verified: compodoc 1.2.1 places label in inputsClass (not propertiesClass) with description 'The label text displayed by the component.' Verified: compodoc 1.2.1 places changed in outputsClass with description 'Emitted when the component value changes.'"
  </evidence>
</pre_verified>

## Findings

1. Finding 1: No story file -- Compodoc integration is untestable end-to-end
   - File: `packages/ngx-smart-components/src/lib/ngx-smart-components/` (entire directory; no `*.stories.ts` present)
   - Severity (initial): Important
   - Description: The full Compodoc + Storybook pipeline is wired (compodocArgs, preview.ts global write, autodocs enabled), but there is no `NgxSmartComponents.stories.ts` file. Without at least one story, the Docs tab generates nothing and the Compodoc descriptions for `label` and `changed` cannot be confirmed as rendering. The commit message for `4e31d8f` explicitly contains an "Outstanding Verification" section: "Run: `npm exec nx run ngx-smart-components:build-storybook` -- verify ... Storybook Docs tab renders label input and changed output descriptions." This was never closed by a follow-up commit.
   - Code context:
     ```typescript
     // packages/ngx-smart-components/src/lib/ngx-smart-components/ngx-smart-components.ts
     export class NgxSmartComponents {
       /** The label text displayed by the component. */
       readonly label = input<string>('');
       /** Emitted when the component value changes. */
       readonly changed = output<string>();
     }
     // No *.stories.ts file exists anywhere in packages/ngx-smart-components/src/
     ```

2. Finding 2: `@ts-ignore` perpetually suppresses type checking on the JSON import
   - File: `packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/preview.ts:1-2`
   - Severity (initial): Suggestion
   - Description: `// @ts-ignore generated at build time` suppresses the "cannot find module '../documentation.json'" error when the file doesn't exist in a fresh checkout. This is the correct pragma choice over `@ts-expect-error` (which would produce TS2578 once `documentation.json` exists). However, once the file IS generated and present, TypeScript would ordinarily infer the JSON's type shape -- the `@ts-ignore` prevents that inference from ever being useful. There is no committed stub or type declaration for `documentation.json`, so fresh-checkout TypeScript always errors, and present-after-build TypeScript is silenced by the pragma. The integration has no fallback if the import resolves to `undefined` at runtime.
   - Code context:
     ```typescript
     // @ts-ignore generated at build time
     import docJson from '../documentation.json';
     (globalThis as unknown as { __STORYBOOK_COMPODOC_JSON__: unknown }).__STORYBOOK_COMPODOC_JSON__ = docJson;
     ```

3. Finding 3: Global `tags: ['autodocs']` in preview opts all future stories in without per-story control
   - File: `packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/preview.ts:6-8`
   - Severity (initial): Suggestion
   - Description: The preview default export sets `tags: ['autodocs']` at the global level, meaning every story added to this Storybook configuration automatically gets an auto-generated Docs page. The canonical Storybook pattern (per `@storybook/angular` template stories in `node_modules`) is to set `tags: ['autodocs']` per story's default export (`meta.tags`), giving each component opt-in control. The global setting is valid API but couples all future stories to autodocs opt-in and removes per-story control unless stories explicitly add `tags: ['!autodocs']` to opt out.
   - Code context:
     ```typescript
     export default {
       tags: ['autodocs'],
     };
     ```

4. Finding 4: `include: ["../src/**/*.ts"]` in storybook tsconfig is broader than needed for Compodoc
   - File: `packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/tsconfig.json:9-18`
   - Severity (initial): Suggestion
   - Description: Compodoc is invoked with `-p packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/tsconfig.json`. The `include` array now contains `../src/**/*.ts` (all TypeScript source), which means Compodoc will parse not just component files but also index barrel files, model interfaces, utilities, etc. For a single-component library this is harmless. For a growing library, it adds Compodoc parsing noise and includes story files (`../src/**/*.stories.ts` is a subset of `../src/**/*.ts`, so the stories-specific include entry is now redundant). The `exclude: ["../**/*.spec.ts"]` correctly removes test files. The broader `../src/**/*.ts` pattern also means the storybook TypeScript compilation includes all source files, which may conflict with Angular Ivy's compilation if files have incompatible types under `emitDecoratorMetadata: true` (storybook tsconfig) vs the project's default `false`.
   - Code context:
     ```json
     "include": [
       "../src/**/*.ts",
       "../src/**/*.stories.ts",
       "../src/**/*.stories.js",
       ...
     ]
     ```

5. Finding 5: `compodocArgs` `-d` flag outputs to package directory rather than a clearly designated generated-output location
   - File: `packages/ngx-smart-components/project.json:51,67`
   - Severity (initial): Suggestion
   - Description: `"-d", "packages/ngx-smart-components"` places `documentation.json` directly in the package source directory, alongside `project.json`, `tsconfig.json`, and other config files. This is correct for the import path in `preview.ts` (`../documentation.json`), but mixing generated artifacts into source roots creates friction (devs may wonder why the directory is "dirty" after a build). A convention like `-d dist/compodoc/ngx-smart-components` with a corresponding `paths` alias in the storybook tsconfig would separate generated from source. The `.gitignore` entry handles the immediate concern but doesn't prevent the cognitive friction.
   - Code context:
     ```json
     "compodocArgs": ["-e", "json", "-d", "packages/ngx-smart-components", "-p", "packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/tsconfig.json"]
     ```

## Relevant File Contents

```typescript
// packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/preview.ts
// @ts-ignore generated at build time
import docJson from '../documentation.json';

(globalThis as unknown as { __STORYBOOK_COMPODOC_JSON__: unknown }).__STORYBOOK_COMPODOC_JSON__ = docJson;

export default {
  tags: ['autodocs'],
};
```

```json
// packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/tsconfig.json
{
  "extends": "../tsconfig.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "emitDecoratorMetadata": true,
    "resolveJsonModule": true,
    "allowSyntheticDefaultImports": true
  },
  "exclude": ["../**/*.spec.ts"],
  "include": [
    "../src/**/*.ts",
    "../src/**/*.stories.ts",
    "../src/**/*.stories.js",
    "../src/**/*.stories.jsx",
    "../src/**/*.stories.tsx",
    "../src/**/*.stories.mdx",
    "*.js",
    "*.ts"
  ]
}
```

```json
// packages/ngx-smart-components/project.json (storybook target, trimmed)
"storybook": {
  "executor": "@storybook/angular:start-storybook",
  "options": {
    "port": 4200,
    "configDir": "packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook",
    "browserTarget": "ngx-smart-components:build-storybook",
    "compodoc": true,
    "compodocArgs": ["-e", "json", "-d", "packages/ngx-smart-components", "-p", "packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/tsconfig.json"]
  }
},
"build-storybook": {
  "executor": "@storybook/angular:build-storybook",
  "options": {
    "outputDir": "dist/storybook/ngx-smart-components",
    "configDir": "packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook",
    "browserTarget": "ngx-smart-components:build-storybook",
    "compodoc": true,
    "compodocArgs": ["-e", "json", "-d", "packages/ngx-smart-components", "-p", "packages/ngx-smart-components/.storybook/tsconfig.json"]
  }
}
```

```typescript
// packages/ngx-smart-components/src/lib/ngx-smart-components/ngx-smart-components.ts
import {
  ChangeDetectionStrategy,
  Component,
  ViewEncapsulation,
  input,
  output,
} from '@angular/core';

/**
 * A smart component that demonstrates Compodoc JSDoc integration with Storybook.
 */
@Component({
  selector: 'smart-ngx-smart-components',
  imports: [],
  template: `<p>NgxSmartComponents works!</p>`,
  styles: `
    :host {
      display: block;
    }
  `,
  encapsulation: ViewEncapsulation.Emulated,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
})
export class NgxSmartComponents {
  /** The label text displayed by the component. */
  readonly label = input<string>('');

  /** Emitted when the component value changes. */
  readonly changed = output<string>();
}
```

## Request

Validate these 5 findings against the code. Confirm or reject each finding. Flag any cross-cutting correctness patterns or API misuse I may have missed. Pay particular attention to whether Finding 2 (`@ts-ignore`) is the correct pragma here given the generated-file constraint, and whether Finding 3 (global autodocs tag) represents an actual misuse of the Storybook 10 API.

